      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Save One Twin, or Lose Both</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Patricia Sette letter on Rev Robert A Sirico's Sept 28 article questions whether doctors would sacrifice failing conjoined twinn if she were able to understand and communicate</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An Unjust Sacrifice,'' by Robert A. Sirico (Op-Ed, Sept. 28):</p>
        <p>More than the other factors in the case of the 8-week-old twins Mary and Jodie, who are joined at the pelvis, it is Mary's inability to comprehend or speak that allows the judges, doctors and ethicists to distance themselves from her humanity.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An Unjust Sacrifice,'' by Robert A. Sirico (Op-Ed, Sept. 28):</p>
        <p>More than the other factors in the case of the 8-week-old twins Mary and Jodie, who are joined at the pelvis, it is Mary's inability to comprehend or speak that allows the judges, doctors and ethicists to distance themselves from her humanity.</p>
        <p>Imagine if Mary were one of a healthy pair of joined 11-year-olds with normal intelligence who suddenly began failing, imperiling both. What judge would volunteer to explain to Mary that tomorrow the doctor was going to kill her?</p>
        <p>PATRICIA SETTE  Concord, Mass., Sept. 28, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
